-le-Chateau, Walloon Brabant, Belgium","Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, France":"Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, France","Picarde, France":"Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Soissons","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from a variant of Old French <i>soçon</i>, <i>sosson</i> ‘companion, partner, workmate’ (from Latin <i>socius</i>), hence a nickname for a laborer, perhaps one who usually worked alongside a horse or ox."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ade","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain origin; it was not in general use before the late 18th century. It may be a Latinate variant of the biblical name   Adah .  However, it has also been explained as a pet form of   Adele   and   Adelaide  , Germanic female names of which the first element is <i>adal</i> ‘noble’. It was borne by a 7th-century abbess of Saint-Julien-des-Prés at Le Mans."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ade Soissons was born about 1058, in Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, France, her father, Guillaume II de Soissons, was 40 and her mother, Adelaide de Vermandois, was 25. She had at least 1 daughter with Hugues de Braine V,  Count of Brienne. She died in 1124, at the age of 67."},"et":{"environ 1058–1124":"umbes 1058–1124","1058–1124":"1058–1124","1030–1100":"1030–1100","1100–1178":"1100–1178","1019–1065":"1019–1065","1035–1079":"1035–1079","1019":"1019","environ 1058":"umbes 1058","1124":"1124","1058":"1058","1079":"1079","1035":"1035","1178":"1178","1100":"1100","1065":"1065","1030":"1030","Braine-le-Chateau, Brabant wallon, Belgique":"Braine-le-Chateau, Brabant wallon, Belgia","Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, France":"Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Picarde, France":"Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"environ 1058–1124":"noin 1058–1124","1058–1124":"1058–1124","1030–1100":"1030–1100","1100–1178":"1100–1178","1019–1065":"1019–1065",